ce:section.ce:para:
For electric vehicle (EV) systems to function correctly, high-capacity lithium-ion (Li-ion) battery TM is essential. An experimental study demonstrated that a sandwiched cooling arrangement of copper metal foam filled with PCMs can significantly enhance thermal efficiency by reducing surface temperature and improving temperature distribution (Fig. 32
                        ) [292]. Similarly, incorporating graphene into hydrocarbon-based PCMs has been shown to raise heat conductivity by greater than two orders of magnitude, thus drastically improving TM and the reliability of Li-ion batteries (Fig. 33
                        ) [293]. It has been proposed that Li-ion battery packs can improve their TM performance and reduce thermal contact resistance by using flexible form-stable CPCMs. The optimal phase change temperature of flexible CPCMs may be adjusted by power levels and environmental temperatures, potentially leading to significant temperature reductions [294]. It has been shown that integrating PCM into a passive thermal system of management for batteries effectively lowers the maximum temperature and the temperature variance inside the battery module. This offers a financially sensible way to control battery temperature [183]. The development of inorganic composite PCMs for passive TM has been explored, with inorganic PCMs demonstrating an ability to prevent thermal runaway spread and possible detonation, offering a safer and more environmentally friendly alternative to organic PCMs [295]. The optimization of CPCM/expanded graphite for Li-ion battery TM has been investigated, and it has been found that a mass fraction of 16–20 wt% expanded graphite in the CPCM provides the optimal TM performance [296]. Analytical modeling and optimization investigations of phase change TM have emphasized the need to enhance cell thermal conductivity to maximize the advantages of phase change cooling. The following analyses continue to explore the trade-offs applicable to TM efficiency and energy storage density [297]. The empirical study on the application of CPCM for thermal management of cylindrical Li-ion batteries demonstrated that metal matrix-CPCM could effectively decrease the maximum temperature difference.

Phase change materials (PCMs) are attracting growing attention in research to improve the performance, safety, and lifespan of lithium-ion batteries by improved thermal management. Efficient thermal management is critical for electric vehicle applications, where batteries experience high power usage and fluctuating environmental conditions. PCMs can effectively regulate temperature fluctuations and provide stable temperature states in lithium-ion batteries, thereby allowing their miniaturized design, reduced weight, and improved energy efficiency without active cooling systems (Fig. 34
                        ) [299]. Graphene-enhanced PCMs have the potential to optimize the TM and reliability of Li-ion batteries. With increased thermal conductivity and maintenance of latent heat storage capacity, these advanced materials can transform the performance of Li-ion batteries [192]. PCM-based BTMS for batteries can face challenges in cold weather, potentially reducing the power and energy of Li-ion batteries quickly below 10 °C, which implies the need for specific solutions based on climates (Fig. 35
                        ) [235,300]. The effectiveness of PCMs in cooling Li-ion batteries during overcharge is influenced by a range of factors, including the C-rate, thermal contact resistance, PCM thickness, and melting temperature (Fig. 36
                        ) [301].
